# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: discrete-event-simulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A **discrete-event simulation** (**DES**) models the operation of a system as a (discrete) sequence of events in time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Each event occurs at a particular instant in time and marks a change of state in the system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Between consecutive events, no change in the system is assumed to occur; thus the simulation time can directly jump to the occurrence time of the next event, which is called **next-event time progression**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In addition to next-event time progression, there is also an alternative approach, called **incremental time progression**, where time is broken up into small time slices and the system state is updated according to the set of events/activities happening in the time slice.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Because not every time slice has to be simulated, a next-event time simulation can typically run faster than a corresponding incremental time simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Both forms of DES contrast with continuous simulation in which the system state is changed continuously over time on the basis of a set of differential equations defining the rates of change for state variables.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In the past, these three types of simulation have also been referred to, respectively, as: event scheduling simulation, activity scanning simulation, and process interaction simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] It can also be noted that there are similarities between the implementation of the event queue in event scheduling, and the scheduling queue used in operating systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A common exercise in learning how to build discrete-event simulations is to model a queueing system, such as customers arriving at a bank teller to be served by a clerk.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In this example, the system objects are ***customer*** and ***teller***, while the system events are ***customer-arrival***, ***service-start*** and ***service-end***.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-start* event occurs, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "busy" and a *service-end* follow-up event is scheduled with a delay (obtained from sampling a *service-time* random variable).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] When a *service-end* event occurs, the state variable *queue-length* is decremented by 1 (representing the customer's departure).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] If the state variable *queue-length* is still greater than zero, a *Service-Start* follow-up event is scheduled to happen without any delay.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Otherwise, the state variable *teller-status* is set to "available".
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The random variables that need to be characterized to model this system stochastically are the *interarrival-time* for recurrent *customer-arrival* events and the *service-time* for the delays of *service-end* events.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A system state is a set of variables that captures the salient properties of the system to be studied.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The state trajectory over time S(t) can be mathematically represented by a step function whose value can change whenever an event occurs.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation must keep track of the current simulation time, in whatever measurement units are suitable for the system being modeled.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In discrete-event simulations, as opposed to continuous simulations, time 'hops' because events are instantaneous – the clock skips to the next event start time as the simulation proceeds.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation maintains at least one list of simulation events.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This is sometimes called the *pending event set* because it lists events that are pending as a result of previously simulated event but have yet to be simulated themselves.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] An event is described by the time at which it occurs and a type, indicating the code that will be used to simulate that event.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] It is common for the event code to be parametrized, in which case, the event description also contains parameters to the event code.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The event list is also referred to as the *future event list* (FEL) or *future event set* (FES).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] When events are instantaneous, activities that extend over time are modeled as sequences of events.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Some simulation frameworks allow the time of an event to be specified as an interval, giving the start time and the end time of each event.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Single-threaded simulation engines based on instantaneous events have just one current event.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In contrast, multi-threaded simulation engines and simulation engines supporting an interval-based event model may have multiple current events.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In both cases, there are significant problems with synchronization between current events.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The pending event set is typically organized as a priority queue, sorted by event time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] That is, regardless of the order in which events are added to the event set, they are removed in strictly chronological order.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Various priority queue implementations have been studied in the context of discrete event simulation; alternatives studied have included splay trees, skip lists, calendar queues, and ladder queues.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] On massively-parallel machines, such as multi-core or many-core CPUs, the pending event set can be implemented by relying on non-blocking algorithms, in order to reduce the cost of synchronization among the concurrent threads.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Typically, events are scheduled dynamically as the simulation proceeds.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] For example, in the bank example noted above, the event CUSTOMER-ARRIVAL at time t would, if the CUSTOMER_QUEUE was empty and TELLER was idle, include the creation of the subsequent event CUSTOMER-DEPARTURE to occur at time t+s, where s is a number generated from the SERVICE-TIME distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation needs to generate random variables of various kinds, depending on the system model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This is accomplished by one or more Pseudorandom number generators.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The use of pseudo-random numbers as opposed to true random numbers is a benefit should a simulation need a rerun with exactly the same behavior.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] One of the problems with the random number distributions used in discrete-event simulation is that the steady-state distributions of event times may not be known in advance.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] As a result, the initial set of events placed into the pending event set will not have arrival times representative of the steady-state distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This problem is typically solved by bootstrapping the simulation model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Only a limited effort is made to assign realistic times to the initial set of pending events.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] These events, however, schedule additional events, and with time, the distribution of event times approaches its steady state.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] This is called *bootstrapping* the simulation model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In gathering statistics from the running model, it is important to either disregard events that occur before the steady state is reached or to run the simulation for long enough that the bootstrapping behavior is overwhelmed by steady-state behavior.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] (This use of the term *bootstrapping* can be contrasted with its use in both statistics and computing).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The simulation typically keeps track of the system's statistics, which quantify the aspects of interest.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In the bank example, it is of interest to track the mean waiting times.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In a simulation model, performance metrics are not analytically derived from probability distributions, but rather as averages over replications, that is different runs of the model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Confidence intervals are usually constructed to help assess the quality of the output.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Because events are bootstrapped, theoretically a discrete-event simulation could run forever.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] So the simulation designer must decide when the simulation will end.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Typical choices are "at time t" or "after processing n number of events" or, more generally, "when statistical measure X reaches the value x".
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Pidd (1998) has proposed the three-phased approach to discrete event simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] In this approach, the first phase is to jump to the next chronological event.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The second phase is to execute all events that unconditionally occur at that time (these are called B-events).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The third phase is to execute all events that conditionally occur at that time (these are called C-events).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The three phase approach is a refinement of the event-based approach in which simultaneous events are ordered so as to make the most efficient use of computer resources.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The three-phase approach is used by a number of commercial simulation software packages, but from the user's point of view, the specifics of the underlying simulation method are generally hidden.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation approaches are particularly well equipped to help users diagnose issues in complex environments.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] The theory of constraints illustrates the importance of understanding bottlenecks in a system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Identifying and removing bottlenecks allows improving processes and the overall system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] For instance, in manufacturing enterprises bottlenecks may be created by excess inventory, overproduction, variability in processes and variability in routing or sequencing.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] By accurately documenting the system with the help of a simulation model it is possible to gain a bird’s eye view of the entire system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A working model of a system allows management to understand performance drivers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation can be built to include any number of performance indicators such as worker utilization, on-time delivery rate, scrap rate, cash cycles, and so on.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] An operating theater is generally shared between several surgical disciplines.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Through better understanding the nature of these procedures it may be possible to increase the patient throughput.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Example: If a heart surgery takes on average four hours, changing an operating room schedule from eight available hours to nine will not increase patient throughput.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] On the other hand, if a hernia procedure takes on average twenty minutes providing an extra hour may also not yield any increased throughput if the capacity and average time spent in the recovery room is not considered.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Many systems improvement ideas are built on sound principles, proven methodologies (Lean, Six Sigma, TQM, etc.) yet fail to improve the overall system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] A simulation model allows the user to understand and test a performance improvement idea in the context of the overall system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Simulation modeling is commonly used to model potential investments.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Through modeling investments decision-makers can make informed decisions and evaluate potential alternatives.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] Discrete event simulation is used in computer network to simulate new protocols, different system architectures (distributed, hierarchical, centralised, P2P) before actual deployment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/discrete-event-simulation] It is possible to define different evaluation metrics, such as service time, bandwidth, dropped packets, resource consumption, and so on.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The process's name derives from the fact that the number of points in any given finite region follows a Poisson distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The process and the distribution are named after French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The process itself was discovered independently and repeatedly in several settings, including experiments on radioactive decay, telephone call arrivals and actuarial science.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This point process is used as a mathematical model for seemingly random processes in numerous disciplines including astronomy, biology, ecology, geology, seismology, physics, economics, image processing, and telecommunications.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The Poisson point process is often defined on the real number line, where it can be viewed as a stochastic process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It is used, for example, in queueing theory to model random events distributed in time, such as the arrival of customers at a store, phone calls at an telephone exchange, or the occurrence of earthquakes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, the point process—also known as a **spatial Poisson process**—can represent the locations of scattered objects such as transmitters in a wireless network, particles colliding into a particle detector, or trees in a forest.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The process is widely used in mathematical models and in related fields, including spatial point processes, stochastic geometry, spatial statistics and continuum percolation theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The point process depends on a single mathematical object, which, depending on the context, may be a constant, a locally integrable function or, in more general settings, a Radon measure.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the first case, the constant, known as the **rate** or **intensity**, is the average density of the points in the Poisson process located in some region of space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The resulting point process is called a **homogeneous** or **stationary Poisson point process**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the second case, the point process is called an **inhomogeneous** or **nonhomogeneous** **Poisson point process**, and the average density of points depend on the location of the underlying space of the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The word *point* is often omitted, but there are other *Poisson processes* of objects, which, instead of points, consist of more complicated mathematical objects such as lines and polygons, and such processes can be based on the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Both the homogeneous and nonhomogeneous Poisson point processes are particular cases of the generalized renewal process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Depending on the setting, the process has several equivalent definitions as well as definitions of varying generality owing to its many applications and characterizations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Consequently, the notation, terminology and level of mathematical rigour used to define and study the Poisson point process and points processes in general vary according to the context.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Despite all this, the Poisson point process has two key properties—the Poisson property and the independence property— that play an essential role in all settings where the Poisson point process is used.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The two properties are not logically independent; indeed, the Poisson distribution of point counts implies the independence property, while in the converse direction the assumptions that: (i) the point process is simple, (ii) has no fixed atoms, and (iii) is a.s. boundedly finite are required.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] A Poisson point process is characterized via the Poisson distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle n!}$ denotes factorial and the parameter ${\textstyle \Lambda }$ determines the shape of the distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] By definition, a Poisson point process has the property that the number of points in a bounded region of the process's underlying space is a Poisson-distributed random variable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Consider a collection of disjoint and bounded subregions of the underlying space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] By definition, the number of points of a Poisson point process in each bounded subregion will be completely independent of all the others.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This property is known under several names such as *complete randomness*, *complete independence*, or *independent scattering* and is common to all Poisson point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, there is a lack of interaction between different regions and the points in general, which motivates the Poisson process being sometimes called a *purely* or *completely* random process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The parameter, called **rate** or **intensity**, is related to the expected (or average) number of Poisson points existing in some bounded region, where *rate* is usually used when the underlying space has one dimension.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ can be interpreted as the average number of points per some unit of extent such as length, area, volume, or time, depending on the underlying mathematical space, and it is also called the *mean density* or *mean rate*; see Terminology.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The homogeneous Poisson point process, when considered on the positive half-line, can be defined as a counting process, a type of stochastic process, which can be denoted as ${\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] A counting process represents the total number of occurrences or events that have happened up to and including time ${\textstyle t}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The Poisson counting process can also be defined by stating that the time differences between events of the counting process are exponential variables with mean ${\textstyle 1/\lambda }$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The time differences between the events or arrivals are known as **interarrival** or **interoccurrence** times.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Interpreted as a point process, a Poisson point process can be defined on the real line by considering the number of points of the process in the interval ${\textstyle (a,b]}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, ${\textstyle N(a,b]}$ is a Poisson random variable with mean ${\textstyle \lambda (b-a)}$ , where ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the number of points in any two disjoint intervals, say, ${\textstyle (a_{1},b_{1}]}$ and ${\textstyle (a_{2},b_{2}]}$ are independent of each other, and this extends to any finite number of disjoint intervals.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the queueing theory context, one can consider a point existing (in an interval) as an *event*, but this is different to the word event in the probability theory sense.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It follows that ${\textstyle \lambda }$ is the expected number of *arrivals* that occur per unit of time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, for any finite ${\textstyle t>0}$ , the random variable ${\textstyle N(a+t,b+t]}$ is independent of ${\textstyle t}$ , so it is also called a stationary Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\operatorname {E}$ denotes the expectation operator.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, the parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ of the Poisson process coincides with the *density* of points.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the homogeneous Poisson point process adheres to its own form of the (strong) law of large numbers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle \lim }$ denotes the limit of a function, and $\lambda$ is expected number of arrivals occurred per unit of time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The distance between two consecutive points of a point process on the real line will be an exponential random variable with parameter ${\textstyle \lambda }$ (or equivalently, mean ${\textstyle 1/\lambda }$ ).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] A point process is called a **simple point process** when the probability of any of its two points coinciding in the same position, on the underlying space, is zero.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For point processes in general on the real line, the property of orderliness implies that the process is simple, which is the case for the homogeneous Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] On the real line, the Poisson process is a type of continuous-time Markov process known as a birth process, a special case of the birth–death process (with just births and zero deaths).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] More complicated processes with the Markov property, such as Markov arrival processes, have been defined where the Poisson process is a special case.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If the homogeneous Poisson process is considered just on the half-line ${\textstyle [0,\infty )}$ , which can be the case when ${\textstyle t}$ represents time then the resulting process is not truly invariant under translation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In that case the Poisson process is no longer stationary, according to some definitions of stationarity.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] There have been many applications of the homogeneous Poisson process on the real line in an attempt to model seemingly random and independent events occurring.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It has a fundamental role in queueing theory, which is the probability field of developing suitable stochastic models to represent the random arrival and departure of certain phenomena.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, customers arriving and being served or phone calls arriving at a phone exchange can be both studied with techniques from queueing theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The homogeneous Poisson process on the real line is considered one of the simplest stochastic processes for counting random numbers of points.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This process can be generalized in a number of ways.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] One possible generalization is to extend the distribution of interarrival times from the exponential distribution to other distributions, which introduces the stochastic process known as a renewal process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Another generalization is to define the Poisson point process on higher dimensional spaces such as the plane.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] A **spatial Poisson process** is a Poisson point process defined in the plane $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For its mathematical definition, one first considers a bounded, open or closed (or more precisely, Borel measurable) region ${\textstyle B}$ of the plane.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points of a point process $\textstyle N$ existing in this region $\textstyle B\subset \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is a random variable, denoted by $\textstyle N(B)$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ denotes the area of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For some finite integer $\textstyle k\geq 1$ , we can give the finite-dimensional distribution of the homogeneous Poisson point process by first considering a collection of disjoint, bounded Borel (measurable) sets $\textstyle B_{1},\dots ,B_{k}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points of the point process $\textstyle N$ existing in $\textstyle B_{i}$ can be written as $\textstyle N(B_{i})$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The spatial Poisson point process features prominently in spatial statistics, stochastic geometry, and continuum percolation theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This point process is applied in various physical sciences such as a model developed for alpha particles being detected.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In recent years, it has been frequently used to model seemingly disordered spatial configurations of certain wireless communication networks.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, models for cellular or mobile phone networks have been developed where it is assumed the phone network transmitters, known as base stations, are positioned according to a homogeneous Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The previous homogeneous Poisson point process immediately extends to higher dimensions by replacing the notion of area with (high dimensional) volume.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ now denotes the $\textstyle d$ -dimensional volume of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, for a collection of disjoint, bounded Borel sets $\textstyle B_{1},\dots ,B_{k}\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ , let $\textstyle N(B_{i})$ denote the number of points of $\textstyle N$ existing in $\textstyle B_{i}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Homogeneous Poisson point processes do not depend on the position of the underlying space through its parameter $\textstyle \lambda$ , which implies it is both a stationary process (invariant to translation) and an isotropic (invariant to rotation) stochastic process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Similarly to the one-dimensional case, the homogeneous point process is restricted to some bounded subset of ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}}$ , then depending on some definitions of stationarity, the process is no longer stationary.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If the homogeneous point process is defined on the real line as a mathematical model for occurrences of some phenomenon, then it has the characteristic that the positions of these occurrences or events on the real line (often interpreted as time) will be uniformly distributed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] More specifically, if an event occurs (according to this process) in an interval $\textstyle (a,b]$ where $\textstyle a\leq b$ , then its location will be a uniform random variable defined on that interval.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the homogeneous point process is sometimes called the *uniform* Poisson point process (see Terminology).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This uniformity property extends to higher dimensions in the Cartesian coordinate, but not in, for example, polar coordinates.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The **inhomogeneous** or **nonhomogeneous** **Poisson point process** (see Terminology) is a Poisson point process with a Poisson parameter set as some location-dependent function in the underlying space on which the Poisson process is defined.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] On the real line, the inhomogeneous or non-homogeneous Poisson point process has mean measure given by a one-dimensional integral.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For two real numbers $\textstyle a$ and $\textstyle b$ , where $\textstyle a\leq b$ , denote by $\textstyle N(a,b]$ the number points of an inhomogeneous Poisson process with intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (t)$ occurring in the interval $\textstyle (a,b]$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] which means that the random variable $\textstyle N(a,b]$ is a Poisson random variable with mean $\textstyle \operatorname {E} [N(a,b]]=\Lambda (a,b)$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] A feature of the one-dimension setting, is that an inhomogeneous Poisson process can be transformed into a homogeneous by a monotone transformation or mapping, which is achieved with the inverse of $\textstyle \Lambda$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The inhomogeneous Poisson point process, when considered on the positive half-line, is also sometimes defined as a counting process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] With this interpretation, the process, which is sometimes written as $\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}$ , represents the total number of occurrences or events that have happened up to and including time $\textstyle t$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle o(h)$ is asymptotic or little-o notation for $\textstyle o(h)/h\rightarrow 0$ as $\textstyle h\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the case of point processes with refractoriness (e.g., neural spike trains) a stronger version of property 4 applies: $\Pr\{N(t+h)-N(t)\geq 2\}=o(h^{2})$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] An inhomogeneous Poisson process defined in the plane $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is called a **spatial Poisson process** It is defined with intensity function and its intensity measure is obtained performing a surface integral of its intensity function over some region.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where ${\textstyle B}$ is some bounded region in the plane ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{2}}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, ${\textstyle \Lambda (B)}$ corresponds to a surface integral while in ${\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}}$ the integral becomes a ( ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional) volume integral.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] When the real line is interpreted as time, the inhomogeneous process is used in the fields of counting processes and in queueing theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the plane, the Poisson point process is important in the related disciplines of stochastic geometry and spatial statistics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The intensity measure of this point process is dependent on the location of underlying space, which means it can be used to model phenomena with a density that varies over some region.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, the phenomena can be represented as points that have a location-dependent density.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This processes has been used in various disciplines and uses include the study of salmon and sea lice in the oceans, forestry, and search problems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, given a homogeneous Poisson point process on the real line, the probability of finding a single point of the process in a small interval of width ${\textstyle \delta }$ is approximately ${\textstyle \lambda \delta }$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In fact, such intuition is how the Poisson point process is sometimes introduced and its distribution derived.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If a Poisson point process has an intensity measure that is a locally finite and diffuse (or non-atomic), then it is a **simple point process**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For a simple point process, the probability of a point existing at a single point or location in the underlying (state) space is either zero or one.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This implies that, with probability one, no two (or more) points of a Poisson point process coincide in location in the underlying space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Simulating a Poisson point process on a computer is usually done in a bounded region of space, known as a simulation *window*, and requires two steps: appropriately creating a random number of points and then suitably placing the points in a random manner.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Both these two steps depend on the specific Poisson point process that is being simulated.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The number of points ${\textstyle N}$ in the window, denoted here by ${\textstyle W}$ , needs to be simulated, which is done by using a (pseudo)-random number generating function capable of simulating Poisson random variables.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous case with the constant ${\textstyle \lambda }$ , the mean of the Poisson random variable ${\textstyle N}$ is set to ${\textstyle \lambda |W|}$ where ${\textstyle |W|}$ is the length, area or ( ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional) volume of ${\textstyle W}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The second stage requires randomly placing the $\textstyle N$ points in the window $\textstyle W$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous case in one dimension, all points are uniformly and independently placed in the window or interval $\textstyle W$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For higher dimensions in a Cartesian coordinate system, each coordinate is uniformly and independently placed in the window $\textstyle W$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If the window is not a subspace of Cartesian space (for example, inside a unit sphere or on the surface of a unit sphere), then the points will not be uniformly placed in $\textstyle W$ , and suitable change of coordinates (from Cartesian) are needed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For the inhomogeneous case, a couple of different methods can be used depending on the nature of the intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If the intensity function is sufficiently simple, then independent and random non-uniform (Cartesian or other) coordinates of the points can be generated.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For more complicated intensity functions, one can use an acceptance-rejection method, which consists of using (or 'accepting') only certain random points and not using (or 'rejecting') the other points, based on the ratio:.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle x_{i}$ is the point under consideration for acceptance or rejection.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In measure theory, the Poisson point process can be further generalized to what is sometimes known as the **general Poisson point process** or **general Poisson process** by using a Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ , which is a locally finite measure.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In general, this Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ can be atomic, which means multiple points of the Poisson point process can exist in the same location of the underlying space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In this situation, the number of points at $\textstyle x$ is a Poisson random variable with mean $\textstyle \Lambda ({x})$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] But sometimes the converse is assumed, so the Radon measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ is diffuse or non-atomic.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where the density $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ is known, among other terms, as the intensity function.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Despite its name, the Poisson point process was neither discovered nor studied by its namesake.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It is cited as an example of Stigler's law of eponymy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The name arises from the process's inherent relation to the Poisson distribution, derived by Poisson as a limiting case of the binomial distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It describes the probability of the sum of $\textstyle n$ Bernoulli trials with probability $\textstyle p$ , often likened to the number of heads (or tails) after $\textstyle n$ biased coin flips with the probability of a head (or tail) occurring being $\textstyle p$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For some positive constant $\textstyle \Lambda >0$ , as $\textstyle n$ increases towards infinity and $\textstyle p$ decreases towards zero such that the product $\textstyle np=\Lambda$ is fixed, the Poisson distribution more closely approximates that of the binomial.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In 1841, Poisson derived the Poisson distribution by studying the binomial distribution in the limit as $\textstyle p$ goes to zero and $\textstyle n$ goes to infinity.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The distribution appears only once in Poisson's work, and the result was not well known during his time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Over the following years, others used the distribution without citing Poisson, including Philipp Ludwig von Seidel and Ernst Abbe.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] At the end of the 19th century, Ladislaus Bortkiewicz revived interest in the distribution by citing Poisson and using real data on the number of deaths from horse kicks in the Prussian army.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] There are a number of claims for early uses or discoveries of the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] This work inspired Simon Newcomb to study the problem and to calculate the Poisson distribution as an approximation for the binomial distribution in 1860.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] At the beginning of the 20th century the Poisson process (in one dimension) would arise independently in different situations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In Sweden 1903, Filip Lundberg published a thesis containing work, now considered fundamental and pioneering, where he proposed to model insurance claims with a homogeneous Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Erlang derived the Poisson distribution in 1909 when developing a mathematical model for the number of incoming phone calls in a finite time interval.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Erlang unaware of Poisson's earlier work and assumed that the number phone calls arriving in each interval of time were independent of each other.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] He then found the limiting case, which is effectively recasting the Poisson distribution as a limit of the binomial distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In 1910 Ernest Rutherford and Hans Geiger published experimental results on counting alpha particles.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Their experimental work had mathematical contributions from Harry Bateman, who derived Poisson probabilities as a solution to a family of differential equations, though the solution had been derived earlier, resulting in the independent discovery of the Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] After this time, there were many studies and applications of the Poisson process, but its early history is complicated, which has been explained by the various applications of the process in numerous fields by biologists, ecologists, engineers and various physical scientists.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The early results were published in different languages and in different settings, with no standard terminology and notation used.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, in 1922 Swedish chemist and Nobel Laureate Theodor Svedberg proposed a model in which a spatial Poisson point process is the underlying process to study how plants are distributed in plant communities.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] A number of mathematicians started studying the process in the early 1930s, and important contributions were made by Andrey Kolmogorov, William Feller and Aleksandr Khinchin, among others.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the field of teletraffic engineering, mathematicians and statisticians studied and used Poisson and other point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The Swede Conny Palm in his 1943 dissertation studied the Poisson and other point processes in the one-dimensional setting by examining them in terms of the statistical or stochastic dependence between the points in time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In his work exists the first known recorded use of the term *point processes* as *Punktprozesse* in German.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It is believed that William Feller was the first in print to refer to it as the *Poisson process* in a 1940 paper.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Although the Swede Ove Lundberg used the term *Poisson process* in his 1940 PhD dissertation, in which Feller was acknowledged as an influence, it has been claimed that Feller coined the term before 1940.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It has been remarked that both Feller and Lundberg used the term as though it were well-known, implying it was already in spoken use by then.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The terminology of point process theory in general has been criticized for being too varied.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In addition to the word *point* often being omitted, the homogeneous Poisson (point) process is also called a *stationary* Poisson (point) process, as well as *uniform* Poisson (point) process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The inhomogeneous Poisson point process, as well as being called *nonhomogeneous*, is also referred to as the *non-stationary* Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The term *point process* has been criticized, as the term *process* can suggest over time and space, so *random point field*, resulting in the terms *Poisson random point field* or *Poisson point field* being also used.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The underlying mathematical space of the Poisson point process is called a **carrier space**, or **state space**, though the latter term has a different meaning in the context of stochastic processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the context of point processes, the term "state space" can mean the space on which the point process is defined such as the real line, which corresponds to the index set or parameter set in stochastic process terminology.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ is called the *intensity measure*, *mean measure*, or *parameter measure*, as there are no standard terms.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If $\textstyle \Lambda$ has a derivative or density, denoted by $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ , is called the *intensity function* of the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For the homogeneous Poisson point process, the derivative of the intensity measure is simply a constant $\textstyle \lambda >0$ , which can be referred to as the *rate*, usually when the underlying space is the real line, or the *intensity*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] It is also called the *mean rate* or the *mean density* or *rate*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For $\textstyle \lambda =1$ , the corresponding process is sometimes referred to as the *standard Poisson* (point) process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The extent of the Poisson point process is sometimes called the *exposure*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The notation of the Poisson point process depends on its setting and the field it is being applied in.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, on the real line, the Poisson process, both homogeneous or inhomogeneous, is sometimes interpreted as a counting process, and the notation $\textstyle \{N(t),t\geq 0\}$ is used to represent the Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Another reason for varying notation is due to the theory of point processes, which has a couple of mathematical interpretations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] For example, a simple Poisson point process may be considered as a random set, which suggests the notation $\textstyle x\in N$ , implying that $\textstyle x$ is a random point belonging to or being an element of the Poisson point process $\textstyle N$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] These different interpretations results in notation being used from mathematical fields such as measure theory and set theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Furthermore, the set theory and integral or measure theory notation can be used interchangeably.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] demonstrates two different ways to write a summation over a point process (see also Campbell's theorem (probability)).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] More specifically, the integral notation on the left-hand side is interpreting the point process as a random counting measure while the sum on the right-hand side suggests a random set interpretation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In probability theory, operations are applied to random variables for different purposes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Sometimes these operations are regular expectations that produce the average or variance of a random variable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Others, such as characteristic functions (or Laplace transforms) of a random variable can be used to uniquely identify or characterize random variables and prove results like the central limit theorem.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In the theory of point processes there exist analogous mathematical tools which usually exist in the forms of measures and functionals instead of moments and functions respectively.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] One version of Campbell's theorem involves the Laplace functional of the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The probability generating function of non-negative integer-valued random variable leads to the probability generating functional being defined analogously with respect to any non-negative bounded function $\textstyle v$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ such that $\textstyle 0\leq v(x)\leq 1$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where the product is performed for all the points in ${\textstyle N}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] If the intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ of $\textstyle {N}$ is locally finite, then the ${\textstyle G}$ is well-defined for any measurable function $\textstyle u$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B|$ is the length, area or volume (or more generally, the Lebesgue measure) of $\textstyle B$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The Mecke equation characterizes the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Let $\mathbb {N} _{\sigma }$ be the space of all $\sigma$ -finite measures on some general space ${\mathcal {Q}}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] where $\textstyle |B_{i}|$ is the length, area, or volume (or more generally, the Lebesgue measure) of $\textstyle B_{i}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] Simple point processes are completely characterized by their void probabilities.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] In other words, complete information of a simple point process is captured entirely in its void probabilities, and two simple point processes have the same void probabilities if and if only if they are the same point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] The case for Poisson process is sometimes known as **Rényi’s theorem**, which is named after Alfréd Rényi who discovered the result for the case of a homogeneous point process in one dimension.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p01] then $\textstyle N$ is a Poisson point process with intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Mathematical operations can be performed on point processes to get new point processes and develop new mathematical models for the locations of certain objects.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] One example of an operation is known as thinning which entails deleting or removing the points of some point process according to a rule, creating a new process with the remaining points (the deleted points also form a point process).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] For the Poisson process, the independent $\textstyle p(x)$ -thinning operations results in another Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] This thinning result of the Poisson point process is sometimes known as **Prekopa's theorem**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The two separate Poisson point processes formed respectively from the removed and kept points are stochastically independent of each other.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, if a region is known to contain $\textstyle n$ kept points (from the original Poisson point process), then this will have no influence on the random number of removed points in the same region.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] This ability to randomly create two independent Poisson point processes from one is sometimes known as *splitting* the Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, any points located in any of the point processes $\textstyle N_{1},N_{2}\dots$ will also be located in the superposition of these point processes $\textstyle {N}$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, the union of two (or countably more) Poisson processes is another Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The operation clustering is performed when each point $\textstyle x$ of some point process $\textstyle {N}$ is replaced by another (possibly different) point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] If the original process $\textstyle {N}$ is a Poisson point process, then the resulting process $\textstyle {N}_{c}$ is called a Poisson cluster point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] A mathematical model may require randomly moving points of a point process to other locations on the underlying mathematical space, which gives rise to a point process operation known as displacement or translation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] One version of the displacement theorem involves a Poisson point process $\textstyle {N}$ on $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ with intensity function $\textstyle \lambda (x)$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In other words, after each random and independent displacement of points, the original Poisson point process still exists.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The displacement theorem can be extended such that the Poisson points are randomly displaced from one Euclidean space $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ to another Euclidean space $\textstyle \mathbb {R} ^{d'}$ , where $\textstyle d'\geq 1$ is not necessarily equal to $\textstyle d$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Another property that is considered useful is the ability to map a Poisson point process from one underlying space to another space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] If the mapping (or transformation) adheres to some conditions, then the resulting mapped (or transformed) collection of points also form a Poisson point process, and this result is sometimes referred to as the **mapping theorem**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The theorem involves some Poisson point process with mean measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ on some underlying space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] If the locations of the points are mapped (that is, the point process is transformed) according to some function to another underlying space, then the resulting point process is also a Poisson point process but with a different mean measure $\textstyle \Lambda '$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] with no atoms, where $\textstyle B$ is a Borel set and $\textstyle f^{-1}$ denotes the inverse of the function $\textstyle f$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] If $\textstyle {N}$ is a Poisson point process, then the new process $\textstyle {N}'$ is also a Poisson point process with the intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda '$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The tractability of the Poisson process means that sometimes it is convenient to approximate a non-Poisson point process with a Poisson one.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The overall aim is to approximate both the number of points of some point process and the location of each point by a Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] There a number of methods that can be used to justify, informally or rigorously, approximating the occurrence of random events or phenomena with suitable Poisson point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The more rigorous methods involve deriving upper bounds on the probability metrics between the Poisson and non-Poisson point processes, while other methods can be justified by less formal heuristics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] One method for approximating random events or phenomena with Poisson processes is called the **clumping heuristic**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The general heuristic or principle involves using the Poisson point process (or Poisson distribution) to approximate events, which are considered rare or unlikely, of some stochastic process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In some cases these rare events are close to being independent, hence a Poisson point process can be used.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method is a mathematical technique originally developed for approximating random variables such as Gaussian and Poisson variables, which has also been applied to point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method can be used to derive upper bounds on probability metrics, which give way to quantify how different two random mathematical objects vary stochastically.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Upperbounds on probability metrics such as total variation and Wasserstein distance have been derived.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Researchers have applied Stein's method to Poisson point processes in a number of ways, such as using Palm calculus.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Techniques based on Stein's method have been developed to factor into the upper bounds the effects of certain point process operations such as thinning and superposition.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Stein's method has also been used to derive upper bounds on metrics of Poisson and other processes such as the Cox point process, which is a Poisson process with a random intensity measure.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In general, when an operation is applied to a general point process the resulting process is usually not a Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] For example, if a point process, other than a Poisson, has its points randomly and independently displaced, then the process would not necessarily be a Poisson point process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Such convergence work is directly related to the results known as the Palm–Khinchin equations, which has its origins in the work of Conny Palm and Aleksandr Khinchin, and help explains why the Poisson process can often be used as a mathematical model of various random phenomena.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson point process can be generalized by, for example, changing its intensity measure or defining on more general mathematical spaces.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] These generalizations can be studied mathematically as well as used to mathematically model or represent physical phenomena.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson-type random measures (PT) are a family of three random counting measures which are closed under restriction to a subspace, i.e. closed under Point process operation#Thinning.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] These random measures are examples of the mixed binomial process and share the distributional self-similarity property of the Poisson random measure.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] They are the only members of the canonical non-negative power series family of distributions to possess this property and include the Poisson distribution, negative binomial distribution, and binomial distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The Poisson random measure is independent on disjoint subspaces, whereas the other PT random measures (negative binomial and binomial) have positive and negative covariances.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The PT random measures are discussed and include the Poisson random measure, negative binomial random measure, and binomial random measure.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In general, the concept of distance is of practical interest for applications, while topological structure is needed for Palm distributions, meaning that point processes are usually defined on mathematical spaces with metrics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Furthermore, a realization of a point process can be considered as a counting measure, so points processes are types of random measures known as random counting measures.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] In this context, the Poisson and other point processes have been studied on a locally compact second countable Hausdorff space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] A **Cox point process**, **Cox process** or **doubly stochastic Poisson process** is a generalization of the Poisson point process by letting its intensity measure $\textstyle \Lambda$ to be also random and independent of the underlying Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The process is named after David Cox who introduced it in 1955, though other Poisson processes with random intensities had been independently introduced earlier by Lucien Le Cam and Maurice Quenouille.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The intensity measure may be a realization of random variable or a random field.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] For example, if the logarithm of the intensity measure is a Gaussian random field, then the resulting process is known as a *log Gaussian Cox process*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] More generally, the intensity measures is a realization of a non-negative locally finite random measure.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] Cox point processes exhibit a *clustering* of points, which can be shown mathematically to be larger than those of Poisson point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The generality and tractability of Cox processes has resulted in them being used as models in fields such as spatial statistics and wireless networks.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] For a given point process, each random point of a point process can have a random mathematical object, known as a **mark**, randomly assigned to it.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] These marks can be as diverse as integers, real numbers, lines, geometrical objects or other point processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The pair consisting of a point of the point process and its corresponding mark is called a marked point, and all the marked points form a **marked point process**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] It is often assumed that the random marks are independent of each other and identically distributed, yet the mark of a point can still depend on the location of its corresponding point in the underlying (state) space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] If the underlying point process is a Poisson point process, then the resulting point process is a **marked Poisson point process**.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] If a general point process is defined on some mathematical space and the random marks are defined on another mathematical space, then the marked point process is defined on the Cartesian product of these two spaces.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] where $\textstyle B\subset \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ is a Borel measurable set.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/poisson-point-process-p02] The failure process with the exponential smoothing of intensity functions (FP-ESI) is an extension of the nonhomogeneous Poisson process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queueing theory has its origins in research by Agner Krarup Erlang, who created models to describe the system of incoming calls at the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange Company.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] These ideas were seminal to the field of teletraffic engineering and have since seen applications in telecommunications, traffic engineering, computing, project management, and particularly industrial engineering, where they are applied in the design of factories, shops, offices, and hospitals.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queueing theory is one of the major areas of study in the discipline of management science.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Through management science, businesses are able to solve a variety of problems using different scientific and mathematical approaches.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queueing analysis is the probabilistic analysis of waiting lines, and thus the results, also referred to as the operating characteristics, are probabilistic rather than deterministic.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The overall goal of queueing analysis is to compute these characteristics for the current system and then test several alternatives that could lead to improvement.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Computing the operating characteristics for the current system and comparing the values to the characteristics of the alternative systems allows managers to see the pros and cons of each potential option.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] These systems help in the final decision making process by showing ways to increase savings, reduce waiting time, improve efficiency, etc.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The main queueing models that can be used are the single-server waiting line system and the multiple-server waiting line system, which are discussed further below.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] These models can be further differentiated depending on whether service times are constant or undefined, the queue length is finite, the calling population is finite, etc.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] A *queue* or *queueing node* can be thought of as nearly a black box.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] *Jobs* (also called *customers* or *requests*, depending on the field) arrive to the queue, possibly wait some time, take some time being processed, and then depart from the queue.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] However, the queueing node is not quite a pure black box since some information is needed about the inside of the queueing node.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The queue has one or more *servers* which can each be paired with an arriving job.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] When the job is completed and departs, that server will again be free to be paired with another arriving job.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] An analogy often used is that of the cashier at a supermarket.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Customers arrive, are processed by the cashier, and depart.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Each cashier processes one customer at a time, and hence this is a queueing node with only one server.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] A setting where a customer will leave immediately if the cashier is busy when the customer arrives, is referred to as a queue with no *buffer* (or no *waiting area*).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] A setting with a waiting zone for up to *n* customers is called a queue with a buffer of size *n*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The behaviour of a single queue (also called a *queueing node*) can be described by a birth–death process, which describes the arrivals and departures from the queue, along with the number of jobs currently in the system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] If *k* denotes the number of jobs in the system (either being serviced or waiting if the queue has a buffer of waiting jobs), then an arrival increases *k* by 1 and a departure decreases *k* by 1.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The system transitions between values of *k* by *births* and *deaths*, which occur at the arrival rates $\lambda _{i}$ and the departure rates $\mu _{i}$ for each job i .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] For a queue, these rates are generally considered not to vary with the number of jobs in the queue, so a single average rate of arrivals/departures per unit time is assumed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The steady state equations for the birth-and-death process, known as the balance equations, are as follows.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Here $P_{n}$ denotes the steady state probability to be in state *n*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] which, together with the equation for $P_{n}$ $(n\geq 1)$ , fully describes the required steady state probabilities.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Single queueing nodes are usually described using Kendall's notation in the form A/S/*c* where *A* describes the distribution of durations between each arrival to the queue, *S* the distribution of service times for jobs, and *c* the number of servers at the node.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] For an example of the notation, the M/M/1 queue is a simple model where a single server serves jobs that arrive according to a Poisson process (where inter-arrival durations are exponentially distributed) and have exponentially distributed service times (the M denotes a Markov process).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In an M/G/1 queue, the G stands for *general* and indicates an arbitrary probability distribution for service times.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Further, let $E_{n}$ represent the number of times the system enters state *n*, and $L_{n}$ represent the number of times the system leaves state *n*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] That is, the number of times the system leaves a state differs by at most 1 from the number of times it enters that state, since it will either return into that state at some time in the future ( $E_{n}=L_{n}$ ) or not ( $\left\vert E_{n}-L_{n}\right\vert =1$ ).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] When the system arrives at a steady state, the arrival rate should be equal to the departure rate.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] A common basic queueing system is attributed to Erlang and is a modification of Little's Law.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Assuming an exponential distribution for the rates, the waiting time *W* can be defined as the proportion of arrivals that are served.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The two-stage one-box model is common in epidemiology.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In 1909, Agner Krarup Erlang, a Danish engineer who worked for the Copenhagen Telephone Exchange, published the first paper on what would now be called queueing theory.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] He modeled the number of telephone calls arriving at an exchange by a Poisson process and solved the M/D/1 queue in 1917 and M/D/*k* queueing model in 1920.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] If the node has more jobs than servers, then jobs will queue and wait for service.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The M/G/1 queue was solved by Felix Pollaczek in 1930, a solution later recast in probabilistic terms by Aleksandr Khinchin and now known as the Pollaczek–Khinchine formula.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] After the 1940s, queueing theory became an area of research interest to mathematicians.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In 1953, David George Kendall solved the GI/M/*k* queue and introduced the modern notation for queues, now known as Kendall's notation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In 1957, Pollaczek studied the GI/G/1 using an integral equation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] John Kingman gave a formula for the mean waiting time in a G/G/1 queue, now known as Kingman's formula.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Leonard Kleinrock worked on the application of queueing theory to message switching in the early 1960s and packet switching in the early 1970s.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] His initial contribution to this field was his doctoral thesis at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1962, published in book form in 1964.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] His theoretical work published in the early 1970s underpinned the use of packet switching in the ARPANET, a forerunner to the Internet.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The matrix geometric method and matrix analytic methods have allowed queues with phase-type distributed inter-arrival and service time distributions to be considered.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Systems with coupled orbits are an important part in queueing theory in the application to wireless networks and signal processing.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Modern day application of queueing theory concerns among other things product development where (material) products have a spatiotemporal existence, in the sense that products have a certain volume and a certain duration.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Problems such as performance metrics for the M/G/*k* queue remain an open problem.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] this principle states that customers are served one at a time and that the customer that has been waiting the longest is served first.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Service capacity is shared equally between customers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] (ROS), this discipline states that the next job served is selected at random from the jobs waiting in the queue.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Customers with high priority are served first.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] (where a job in service can be interrupted by a higher-priority job).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest size.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The next job to be served is the one with the smallest original size.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The next job to serve is the one with the smallest remaining processing requirement.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Server failures occur according to a stochastic (random) process (usually Poisson) and are followed by setup periods during which the server is unavailable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The interrupted customer remains in the service area until server is fixed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Arriving customers not served (either due to the queue having no buffer, or due to balking or reneging by the customer) are also known as *dropouts*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The average rate of dropouts is a significant parameter describing a queue.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queue networks are systems in which multiple queues are connected by *customer routing*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] When a customer is serviced at one node, it can join another node and queue for service, or leave the network.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] For networks of *m* nodes, the state of the system can be described by an *m*–dimensional vector (*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**m*) where *x**i* represents the number of customers at each node.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The simplest non-trivial networks of queues are called tandem queues.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The first significant results in this area were Jackson networks, for which an efficient product-form stationary distribution exists and the mean value analysis (which allows average metrics such as throughput and sojourn times) can be computed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] If the total number of customers in the network remains constant, the network is called a *closed network* and has been shown to also have a product–form stationary distribution by the Gordon–Newell theorem.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] This result was extended to the BCMP network, where a network with very general service time, regimes, and customer routing is shown to also exhibit a product–form stationary distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The normalizing constant can be calculated with the Buzen's algorithm, proposed in 1973.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Networks of customers have also been investigated, such as Kelly networks, where customers of different classes experience different priority levels at different service nodes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Another type of network are G-networks, first proposed by Erol Gelenbe in 1993: these networks do not assume exponential time distributions like the classic Jackson network.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In discrete-time networks where there is a constraint on which service nodes can be active at any time, the max-weight scheduling algorithm chooses a service policy to give optimal throughput in the case that each job visits only a single-person service node.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In the more general case where jobs can visit more than one node, backpressure routing gives optimal throughput.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] A network scheduler must choose a queueing algorithm, which affects the characteristics of the larger network.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Mean-field models consider the limiting behaviour of the empirical measure (proportion of queues in different states) as the number of queues *m* approaches infinity.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The impact of other queues on any given queue in the network is approximated by a differential equation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The deterministic model converges to the same stationary distribution as the original model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In a system with high occupancy rates (utilisation near 1), a heavy traffic approximation can be used to approximate the queueing length process by a reflected Brownian motion, Ornstein–Uhlenbeck process, or more general diffusion process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The number of dimensions of the Brownian process is equal to the number of queueing nodes, with the diffusion restricted to the non-negative orthant.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Fluid models are continuous deterministic analogs of queueing networks obtained by taking the limit when the process is scaled in time and space, allowing heterogeneous objects.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] This scaled trajectory converges to a deterministic equation which allows the stability of the system to be proven.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] It is known that a queueing network can be stable but have an unstable fluid limit.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queueing theory finds widespread application in computer science and information technology.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] In networking, for instance, queues are integral to routers and switches, where packets queue up for transmission.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] By applying queueing theory principles, designers can optimize these systems, ensuring responsive performance and efficient resource utilization.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Beyond the technological realm, queueing theory is relevant to everyday experiences.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Whether waiting in line at a supermarket or for public transportation, understanding the principles of queueing theory provides valuable insights into optimizing these systems for enhanced user satisfaction.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] At some point, everyone will be involved in an aspect of queuing.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] What some may view to be an inconvenience could possibly be the most effective method.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queueing theory, a discipline rooted in applied mathematics and computer science, is a field dedicated to the study and analysis of queues, or waiting lines, and their implications across a diverse range of applications.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] This theoretical framework has proven instrumental in understanding and optimizing the efficiency of systems characterized by the presence of queues.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The study of queues is essential in contexts such as traffic systems, computer networks, telecommunications, and service operations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] Queueing theory delves into various foundational concepts, with the arrival process and service process being central.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The arrival process describes the manner in which entities join the queue over time, often modeled using stochastic processes like Poisson processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] The efficiency of queueing systems is gauged through key performance metrics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] These include the average queue length, average wait time, and system throughput.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/queueing-theory] These metrics provide insights into the system's functionality, guiding decisions aimed at enhancing performance and reducing wait times.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A **simulation** is an imitative representation of a process or system that could exist in the real world.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In this broad sense, simulation can often be used interchangeably with model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Sometimes a clear distinction between the two terms is made, in which simulations require the use of models; the model represents the key characteristics or behaviors of the selected system or process, whereas the simulation represents the evolution of the model over time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Another way to distinguish between the terms is to define simulation as experimentation with the help of a model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This definition includes time-independent simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Often, computers are used to execute the simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation is used in many contexts, such as simulation of technology for performance tuning or optimizing, safety engineering, testing, training, education, and video games.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used with scientific modelling of natural systems or human systems to gain insight into their functioning, as in economics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation can be used to show the eventual real effects of alternative conditions and courses of action.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used when the real system cannot be engaged, because it may not be accessible, or it may be dangerous or unacceptable to engage, or it is being designed but not yet built, or it may simply not exist.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Procedures and protocols for model verification and validation are an ongoing field of academic study, refinement, research and development in simulations technology or practice, particularly in the work of computer simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Historically, simulations used in different fields developed largely independently, but 20th-century studies of systems theory and cybernetics combined with the spreading use of computers across all those fields have led to some unification and a more systematic view of the concept.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A *stand-alone simulation* is a simulation running on a single workstation by itself.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A **distributed simulation** is one which uses more than one computer simultaneously, to guarantee access from/to different resources (e.g. multi-users operating different systems, or distributed data sets); a classical example is Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A *synthetic environment* is a computer simulation that can be included in human-in-the-loop simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Data simulation creates artificial data to replicate the behavior of real-world data.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The artificial data is generated using computer models or programs based on specific rules, patterns, or characteristics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This type of data is designed to imitate the operations of real systems, processes, or behaviors, enabling researchers and analysts to study and test scenarios without directly observing or collecting information from the real world.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A computer simulation (or "sim") is an attempt to model a real-life or hypothetical situation on a computer so that it can be studied to see how the system works.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] By changing variables in the simulation, predictions may be made about the behaviour of the system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] It is a tool to virtually investigate the behaviour of the system under study.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Computer simulation has become a useful part of modeling many natural systems in physics, chemistry and biology, and human systems in economics and social science (e.g., computational sociology) as well as in engineering to gain insight into the operation of those systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A good example of the usefulness of using computers to simulate can be found in the field of network traffic simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In such simulations, the model behaviour will change each simulation according to the set of initial parameters assumed for the environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Traditionally, the formal modeling of systems has been via a mathematical model, which attempts to find analytical solutions enabling the prediction of the behaviour of the system from a set of parameters and initial conditions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Computer simulation is often used as an adjunct to, or substitution for, modeling systems for which simple closed form analytic solutions are not possible.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] There are many different types of computer simulation, the common feature they all share is the attempt to generate a sample of representative scenarios for a model in which a complete enumeration of all possible states would be prohibitive or impossible.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Several software packages exist for running computer-based simulation modeling (e.g.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Monte Carlo simulation, stochastic modeling, multimethod modeling) that makes all the modeling almost effortless.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Modern usage of the term "computer simulation" may encompass virtually any computer-based representation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The computer simulates the subject machine.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Accordingly, in theoretical computer science the term *simulation* is a relation between state transition systems, useful in the study of operational semantics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Less theoretically, an interesting application of computer simulation is to simulate computers using computers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] For example, simulators have been used to debug a microprogram or sometimes commercial application programs, before the program is downloaded to the target machine.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Since the operation of the computer is simulated, all of the information about the computer's operation is directly available to the programmer, and the speed and execution of the simulation can be varied at will.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulators may also be used to interpret fault trees, or test VLSI logic designs before they are constructed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Symbolic simulation uses variables to stand for unknown values.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In the field of optimization, simulations of physical processes are often used in conjunction with evolutionary computation to optimize control strategies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation is extensively used for educational purposes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] It is used for cases where it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In such situations they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Often the convenience is to permit mistakes during training for a safety-critical system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulations in education are somewhat like training simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The term 'microworld' is used to refer to educational simulations which model some abstract concept rather than simulating a realistic object or environment, or in some cases model a real-world environment in a simplistic way so as to help a learner develop an understanding of the key concepts.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Normally, a user can create some sort of construction within the microworld that will behave in a way consistent with the concepts being modeled.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Seymour Papert was one of the first to advocate the value of microworlds, and the Logo programming environment developed by Papert is one of the most well-known microworlds.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Project management simulation is increasingly used to train students and professionals in the art and science of project management.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Using simulation for project management training improves learning retention and enhances the learning process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In recent years, there has been increasing use of social simulations for staff training in aid and development agencies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The Carana simulation, for example, was first developed by the United Nations Development Programme, and is now used in a very revised form by the World Bank for training staff to deal with fragile and conflict-affected countries.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Military uses for simulation often involve aircraft or armoured fighting vehicles, but can also target small arms and other weapon systems training.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Specifically, virtual firearms ranges have become the norm in most military training processes and there is a significant amount of data to suggest this is a useful tool for armed professionals.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A **virtual simulation** is a category of simulation that uses simulation equipment to create a **simulated world** for the user.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations allow users to interact with a virtual world.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Virtual worlds operate on platforms of integrated software and hardware components.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In this manner, the system can accept input from the user (e.g., body tracking, voice/sound recognition, physical controllers) and produce output to the user (e.g., visual display, aural display, haptic display) .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations use the aforementioned modes of interaction to produce a sense of immersion for the user.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of input hardware available to accept user input for virtual simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Research in future input systems holds a great deal of promise for virtual simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Systems such as brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) offer the ability to further increase the level of immersion for virtual simulation users.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Lee, Keinrath, Scherer, Bischof, Pfurtscheller proved that naïve subjects could be trained to use a BCI to navigate a virtual apartment with relative ease.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Using the BCI, the authors found that subjects were able to freely navigate the virtual environment with relatively minimal effort.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] It is possible that these types of systems will become standard input modalities in future virtual simulation systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of output hardware available to deliver stimuli to users in virtual simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Many medical simulators involve a computer connected to a plastic simulation of the relevant anatomy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Sophisticated simulators of this type employ a life-size mannequin that responds to injected drugs and can be programmed to create simulations of life-threatening emergencies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In other simulations, visual components of the procedure are reproduced by computer graphics techniques, while touch-based components are reproduced by haptic feedback devices combined with physical simulation routines computed in response to the user's actions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Medical simulations of this sort will often use 3D CT or MRI scans of patient data to enhance realism.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Some medical simulations are developed to be widely distributed (such as web-enabled simulations and procedural simulations that can be viewed via standard web browsers) and can be interacted with using standard computer interfaces, such as the keyboard and mouse.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] An important medical application of a simulator—although, perhaps, denoting a slightly different meaning of *simulator*—is the use of a placebo drug, a formulation that simulates the active drug in trials of drug efficacy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Patient safety is a concern in the medical industry.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Patients have been known to suffer injuries and even death due to management error, and lack of using best standards of care and training.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation is being used to study patient safety, as well as train medical professionals.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Studying patient safety and safety interventions in healthcare is challenging, because there is a lack of experimental control (i.e., patient complexity, system/process variances) to see if an intervention made a meaningful difference (Groves & Manges, 2017).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] An example of innovative simulation to study patient safety is from nursing research.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] (2016) used a high-fidelity simulation to examine nursing safety-oriented behaviors during times such as change-of-shift report.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] However, the value of simulation interventions to translating to clinical practice are is still debatable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] As Nishisaki states, "there is good evidence that simulation training improves provider and team self-efficacy and competence on manikins.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] There is also good evidence that procedural simulation improves actual operational performance in clinical settings." However, there is a need to have improved evidence to show that crew resource management training through simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] One of the largest challenges is showing that team simulation improves team operational performance at the bedside.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Although evidence that simulation-based training actually improves patient outcome has been slow to accrue, today the ability of simulation to provide hands-on experience that translates to the operating room is no longer in doubt.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] One of the largest factors that might impact the ability to have training impact the work of practitioners at the bedside is the ability to empower frontline staff (Stewart, Manges, Ward, 2015).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Another example of an attempt to improve patient safety through the use of simulations training is patient care to deliver just-in-time service or/and just-in-place.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This training consists of 20 minutes of simulated training just before workers report to shift.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] One study found that just in time training improved the transition to the bedside.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The conclusion as reported in Nishisaki (2008) work, was that the simulation training improved resident participation in real cases; but did not sacrifice the quality of service.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] It could be therefore hypothesized that by increasing the number of highly trained residents through the use of simulation training, that the simulation training does, in fact, increase patient safety.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The first medical simulators were simple models of human patients.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Since antiquity, these representations in clay and stone were used to demonstrate clinical features of disease states and their effects on humans.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Models have been found in many cultures and continents.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] These models have been used in some cultures (e.g., Chinese culture) as a "diagnostic" instrument, allowing women to consult male physicians while maintaining social laws of modesty.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Models are used today to help students learn the anatomy of the musculoskeletal system and organ systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The need for a "uniform mechanism to educate, evaluate, and certify simulation instructors for the health care profession" was recognized by McGaghie et al. in their critical review of simulation-based medical education research.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In 2012 the SSH piloted two new certifications to provide recognition to educators in an effort to meet this need.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Active models that attempt to reproduce living anatomy or physiology are recent developments.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The famous "Harvey" mannequin was developed at the University of Miami and is able to recreate many of the physical findings of the cardiology examination, including palpation, auscultation, and electrocardiography.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] More recently, interactive models have been developed that respond to actions taken by a student or physician.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Until recently, these simulations were two dimensional computer programs that acted more like a textbook than a patient.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Computer simulations have the advantage of allowing a student to make judgments, and also to make errors.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The process of iterative learning through assessment, evaluation, decision making, and error correction creates a much stronger learning environment than passive instruction.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulators have been proposed as an ideal tool for assessment of students for clinical skills.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] For patients, "cybertherapy" can be used for sessions simulating traumatic experiences, from fear of heights to social anxiety.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Programmed patients and simulated clinical situations, including mock disaster drills, have been used extensively for education and evaluation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] These "lifelike" simulations are expensive, and lack reproducibility.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] A fully functional "3Di" simulator would be the most specific tool available for teaching and measurement of clinical skills.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Gaming platforms have been applied to create these virtual medical environments to create an interactive method for learning and application of information in a clinical context.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Immersive disease state simulations allow a doctor or HCP to experience what a disease actually feels like.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Using sensors and transducers, symptomatic effects can be delivered to a participant, allowing them to experience the patient’s disease state.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Such a simulator meets the goals of an objective and standardized examination for clinical competence.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This system is superior to examinations that use "standard patients" because it permits the quantitative measurement of competence, as well as reproducing the same objective findings.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The first simulation game may have been created as early as 1947 by Thomas T.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This was a straightforward game that simulated a missile being fired at a target.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The curve of the missile and its speed could be adjusted using several knobs.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In 1958, a computer game called *Tennis for Two* was created by Willy Higginbotham which simulated a tennis game between two players who could both play at the same time using hand controls and was displayed on an oscilloscope.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This was one of the first electronic video games to use a graphical display.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery was used in the film to simulate objects as early as 1972 in *A Computer Animated Hand*, parts of which were shown on the big screen in the 1976 film *Futureworld*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This was followed by the "targeting computer" that young Skywalker turns off in the 1977 film *Star Wars*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The film *Tron* (1982) was the first film to use computer-generated imagery for more than a couple of minutes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s caused 3D simulation to become more widely used and it began to appear in movies and in computer-based games such as Atari's *Battlezone* (1980) and Acornsoft's *Elite* (1984), one of the first wire-frame 3D graphics games for home computers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s made the computer more affordable and more capable than they were in previous decades, which facilitated the rise of computer such as the Xbox gaming.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The first video game consoles released in the 1970s and early 1980s fell prey to the industry crash in 1983, but in 1985, Nintendo released the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) which became one of the best selling consoles in video game history.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In the 1990s, computer games became widely popular with the release of such game as *The Sims* and *Command & Conquer* and the still increasing power of desktop computers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Today, computer simulation games such as *World of Warcraft* are played by millions of people around the world.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] In 1993, the film *Jurassic Park* became the first popular film to use computer-generated graphics extensively, integrating the simulated dinosaurs almost seamlessly into live action scenes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This event transformed the film industry; in 1995, the film *Toy Story* was the first film to use only computer-generated images and by the new millennium computer generated graphics were the leading choice for special effects in films.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The advent of virtual cinematography in the early 2000s has led to an explosion of movies that would have been impossible to shoot without it.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Classic examples are the digital look-alikes of Neo, Smith and other characters in the *Matrix* sequels and the extensive use of physically impossible camera runs in *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery is "the application of the field of 3D computer graphics to special effects".
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] This technology is used for visual effects because they are high in quality, controllable, and can create effects that would not be feasible using any other technology either because of cost, resources or safety.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Computer-generated graphics can be seen in many live-action movies today, especially those of the action genre.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Further, computer-generated imagery has almost completely supplanted hand-drawn animation in children's movies which are increasingly computer-generated only.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Examples of movies that use computer-generated imagery include *Finding Nemo*, *300* and *Iron Man*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation games, as opposed to other genres of video and computer games, represent or simulate an environment accurately.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Moreover, they represent the interactions between the playable characters and the environment realistically.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] These kinds of games are usually more complex in terms of gameplay.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulation games have become incredibly popular among people of all ages.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Popular simulation games include *SimCity* and *Tiger Woods PGA Tour*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] There are also flight simulator and driving simulator games.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulators have been used for entertainment since the Link Trainer in the 1930s.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The first modern simulator ride to open at a theme park was Disney's Star Tours in 1987 soon followed by Universal's The Funtastic World of Hanna-Barbera in 1990 which was the first ride to be done entirely with computer graphics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Simulator rides are the progeny of military training simulators and commercial simulators, but they are different in a fundamental way.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] While military training simulators react realistically to the input of the trainee in real time, ride simulators only feel like they move realistically and move according to prerecorded motion scripts.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] One of the first simulator rides, Star Tours, which cost $32 million, used a hydraulic motion based cabin.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] The movement was programmed by a joystick.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Today's simulator rides, such as The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man include elements to increase the amount of immersion experienced by the riders such as: 3D imagery, physical effects (spraying water or producing scents), and movement through an environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p01] Another important goal of simulation in manufacturing systems is to quantify system performance.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] An automobile simulator provides an opportunity to reproduce the characteristics of real vehicles in a virtual environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] It replicates the external factors and conditions with which a vehicle interacts enabling a driver to feel as if they are sitting in the cab of their own vehicle.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Scenarios and events are replicated with sufficient reality to ensure that drivers become fully immersed in the experience rather than simply viewing it as an educational experience.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The simulator provides a constructive experience for the novice driver and enables more complex exercises to be undertaken by the more mature driver.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For novice drivers, truck simulators provide an opportunity to begin their career by applying best practice.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For mature drivers, simulation provides the ability to enhance good driving or to detect poor practice and to suggest the necessary steps for remedial action.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For companies, it provides an opportunity to educate staff in the driving skills that achieve reduced maintenance costs, improved productivity and, most importantly, to ensure the safety of their actions in all possible situations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A **biomechanics simulator** is a simulation platform for creating dynamic mechanical models built from combinations of rigid and deformable bodies, joints, constraints, and various force actuators.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] It is specialized for creating biomechanical models of human anatomical structures, with the intention to study their function and eventually assist in the design and planning of medical treatment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A biomechanics simulator is used to analyze walking dynamics, study sports performance, simulate surgical procedures, analyze joint loads, design medical devices, and animate human and animal movement.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A neuromechanical simulator combines biomechanical and biologically realistic neural network simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] It allows the user to test hypotheses about the neural basis of behavior in a physically accurate 3D virtual environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A city simulator can be a city-building game but can also be a tool used by urban planners to understand how cities are likely to evolve in response to various policy decisions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] AnyLogic is an example of modern, large-scale urban simulators designed for use by urban planners.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] City simulators are generally agent-based simulations with explicit representations for land use and transportation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] UrbanSim and LEAM are examples of large-scale urban simulation models that are used by metropolitan planning agencies and military bases for land use and transportation planning.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Several Christmas-themed simulations exist, many of which are centered around Santa Claus.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] An example of these simulations are websites which claim to allow the user to track Santa Claus.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Another example of these simulations are websites that claim to allow the user to email or send messages to Santa Claus.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Websites such as emailSanta.com or Santa's former page on the now-defunct Windows Live Spaces by Microsoft use automated programs or scripts to generate personalized replies claimed to be from Santa himself based on user input.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Modern satellite communications systems (SATCOM) are often large and complex with many interacting parts and elements.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In addition, the need for broadband connectivity on a moving vehicle has increased dramatically in the past few years for both commercial and military applications.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] To accurately predict and deliver high quality of service, SATCOM system designers have to factor in terrain as well as atmospheric and meteorological conditions in their planning.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] To deal with such complexity, system designers and operators increasingly turn towards computer models of their systems to simulate real-world operating conditions and gain insights into usability and requirements prior to final product sign-off.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Modeling improves the understanding of the system by enabling the SATCOM system designer or planner to simulate real-world performance by injecting the models with multiple hypothetical atmospheric and environmental conditions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation is often used in the training of civilian and military personnel.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] This usually occurs when it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In such situations, they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions are being increasingly integrated with computer-aided solutions and processes (computer-aided design or CAD, computer-aided manufacturing or CAM, computer-aided engineering or CAE, etc.).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The use of simulation throughout the product lifecycle, especially at the earlier concept and design stages, has the potential of providing substantial benefits.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] These benefits range from direct cost issues such as reduced prototyping and shorter time-to-market to better performing products and higher margins.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] However, for some companies, simulation has not provided the expected benefits.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The successful use of simulation, early in the lifecycle, has been largely driven by increased integration of simulation tools with the entire set of CAD, CAM and product-lifecycle management solutions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions can now function across the extended enterprise in a multi-CAD environment, and include solutions for managing simulation data and processes and ensuring that simulation results are made part of the product lifecycle history.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation training has become a method for preparing people for disasters.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulations can replicate emergency situations and track how learners respond thanks to a lifelike experience.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Disaster preparedness simulations can involve training on how to handle terrorism attacks, natural disasters, pandemic outbreaks, or other life-threatening emergencies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] One organization that has used simulation training for disaster preparedness is CADE (Center for Advancement of Distance Education).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] CADE has used a video game to prepare emergency workers for multiple types of attacks.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The Emergency Simulation Program (ESP) at the British Columbia Institute of Technology (BCIT), Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada is another example of an organization that uses simulation to train for emergency situations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] At the University of Québec in Chicoutimi, a research team at the outdoor research and expertise laboratory (Laboratoire d'Expertise et de Recherche en Plein Air – LERPA) specializes in using wilderness backcountry accident simulations to verify emergency response coordination.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Instructionally, the benefits of emergency training through simulations are that learner performance can be tracked through the system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] This allows the developer to make adjustments as necessary or alert the educator on topics that may require additional attention.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Other advantages are that the learner can be guided or trained on how to respond appropriately before continuing to the next emergency segment—this is an aspect that may not be available in the live environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Some emergency training simulators also allow for immediate feedback, while other simulations may provide a summary and instruct the learner to engage in the learning topic again.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In a live-emergency situation, emergency responders do not have time to waste.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation-training in this environment provides an opportunity for learners to gather as much information as they can and practice their knowledge in a safe environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] They can make mistakes without risk of endangering lives and be given the opportunity to correct their errors to prepare for the real-life emergency.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation is an important feature in engineering systems or any system that involves many processes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For example, in electrical engineering, delay lines may be used to simulate propagation delay and phase shift caused by an actual transmission line.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Similarly, dummy loads may be used to simulate impedance without simulating propagation and is used in situations where propagation is unwanted.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A simulator may imitate only a few of the operations and functions of the unit it simulates.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Most engineering simulations entail mathematical modeling and computer-assisted investigation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] There are many cases, however, where mathematical modeling is not reliable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation of fluid dynamics problems often require both mathematical and physical simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In these cases the physical models require dynamic similitude.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Physical and chemical simulations have also direct realistic uses, rather than research uses; in chemical engineering, for example, process simulations are used to give the process parameters immediately used for operating chemical plants, such as oil refineries.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulators are also used for plant operator training.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] It is called Operator Training Simulator (OTS) and has been widely adopted by many industries from chemical to oil&gas and to the power industry.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] This created a safe and realistic virtual environment to train board operators and engineers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Mimic is capable of providing high fidelity dynamic models of nearly all chemical plants for operator training and control system testing.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Software tools typically calculate biomechanical properties including individual muscle forces, joint forces and moments.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Most of these tools employ standard ergonomic evaluation methods such as the NIOSH lifting equation and Rapid Upper Limb Assessment (RULA).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Some simulations also analyze physiological measures including metabolism, energy expenditure, and fatigue limits Cycle time studies, design and process validation, user comfort, reachability, and line of sight are other human-factors that may be examined in ergonomic simulation packages.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Modeling and simulation of a task can be performed by manually manipulating the virtual human in the simulated environment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Some ergonomics simulation software permits interactive, real-time simulation and evaluation through actual human input via motion capture technologies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] However, motion capture for ergonomics requires expensive equipment and the creation of props to represent the environment or product.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Some applications of ergonomic simulation in include analysis of solid waste collection, disaster management tasks, interactive gaming, automotive assembly line, virtual prototyping of rehabilitation aids, and aerospace product design.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Ford engineers use ergonomics simulation software to perform virtual product design reviews.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Using engineering data, the simulations assist evaluation of assembly ergonomics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The company uses Siemen's Jack and Jill ergonomics simulation software in improving worker safety and efficiency, without the need to build expensive prototypes.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In finance, computer simulations are often used for scenario planning.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Risk-adjusted net present value, for example, is computed from well-defined but not always known (or fixed) inputs.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] By imitating the performance of the project under evaluation, simulation can provide a distribution of NPV over a range of discount rates and other variables.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulations are also often used to test a financial theory or the ability of a financial model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulations are frequently used in financial training to engage participants in experiencing various historical as well as fictional situations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] There are stock market simulations, portfolio simulations, risk management simulations or models and forex simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Such simulations are typically based on stochastic asset models.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Using these simulations in a training program allows for the application of theory into a something akin to real life.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] As with other industries, the use of simulations can be technology or case-study driven.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Flight simulation is mainly used to train pilots outside of the aircraft.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In comparison to training in flight, simulation-based training allows for practicing maneuvers or situations that may be impractical (or even dangerous) to perform in the aircraft while keeping the pilot and instructor in a relatively low-risk environment on the ground.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For example, electrical system failures, instrument failures, hydraulic system failures, and even flight control failures can be simulated without risk to the crew or equipment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Instructors can also provide students with a higher concentration of training tasks in a given period of time than is usually possible in the aircraft.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Flight simulation also provides an economic advantage over training in an actual aircraft.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Once fuel, maintenance, and insurance costs are taken into account, the operating costs of an FSTD are usually substantially lower than the operating costs of the simulated aircraft.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For some large transport category airplanes, the operating costs may be several times lower for the FSTD than the actual aircraft.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Another advantage is reduced environmental impact, as simulators don't contribute directly to carbon or noise emissions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] There also exist "engineering flight simulators" which are a key element of the aircraft design process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Many benefits that come from a lower number of test flights like cost and safety improvements are described above, but there are some unique advantages.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Having a simulator available allows for faster design iteration cycle or using more test equipment than could be fit into a real aircraft.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Bearing resemblance to flight simulators, a **marine simulator** is meant for training of ship personnel.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulators like these are mostly used within maritime colleges, training institutions, and navies.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] They often consist of a replication of a ships' bridge, with the operating console(s), and a number of screens on which the virtual surroundings are projected.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Military simulations, also known informally as war games, are models in which theories of warfare can be tested and refined without the need for actual hostilities.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] They exist in many different forms, with varying degrees of realism.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In recent times, their scope has widened to include not only military but also political and social factors (for example, the Nationlab series of strategic exercises in Latin America).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] While many governments make use of simulation, both individually and collaboratively, little is known about the model's specifics outside professional circles.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Network and distributed systems have been extensively simulated in other to understand the impact of new protocols and algorithms before their deployment in the actual systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The simulation can focus on different levels (physical layer, network layer, application layer), and evaluate different metrics (network bandwidth, resource consumption, service time, dropped packets, system availability).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation techniques have also been applied to payment and securities settlement systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Among the main users are central banks, which are generally responsible for the oversight of market infrastructure and are entitled to contribute to the smooth functioning of payment systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Central banks have been using payment system simulations to evaluate things such as the adequacy or sufficiency of liquidity available ( in the form of account balances and intraday credit limits) to participants (mainly banks) to allow efficient settlement of payments.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The need for liquidity is also dependent on the availability and the type of netting procedures in the systems, thus some of the studies have a focus on system comparisons.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Another application is to evaluate risks related to events such as communication network breakdowns or the inability of participants to send payments (e.g. in case of possible bank failure).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] This kind of analysis falls under the concepts of stress testing or scenario analysis.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A common way to conduct these simulations is to replicate the settlement logics of the real payment or securities settlement systems under analysis and then use real observed payment data.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In case of system comparison or system development, naturally, also the other settlement logics need to be implemented.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] To perform stress testing and scenario analysis, the observed data needs to be altered, e.g. some payments delayed or removed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] To analyze the levels of liquidity, initial liquidity levels are varied.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] System comparisons (benchmarking) or evaluations of new netting algorithms or rules are performed by running simulations with a fixed set of data and varying only the system setups.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] An inference is usually done by comparing the benchmark simulation results to the results of altered simulation setups by comparing indicators such as unsettled transactions or settlement delays.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Project management simulation is simulation used for project management training and analysis.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] It is often used as a training simulation for project managers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In other cases, it is used for what-if analysis and for supporting decision-making in real projects.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Frequently the simulation is conducted using software tools.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A robotics simulator is used to create embedded applications for a specific (or not) robot without being dependent on the 'real' robot.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In some cases, these applications can be transferred to the real robot (or rebuilt) without modifications.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Robotics simulators allow reproducing situations that cannot be 'created' in the real world because of cost, time, or the 'uniqueness' of a resource.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A simulator also allows fast robot prototyping.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Many robot simulators feature physics engines to simulate a robot's dynamics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Such simulations can help predict the impact of how improvements in methods might impact variability, cost, labor time, and the number of transactions at various stages in the process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A full-featured computerized process simulator can be used to depict such models, as can simpler educational demonstrations using spreadsheet software, pennies being transferred between cups based on the roll of a die, or dipping into a tub of colored beads with a scoop.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] In sports, computer simulations are often done to predict the outcome of events and the performance of individual sportspeople.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] They attempt to recreate the event through models built from statistics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The increase in technology has allowed anyone with knowledge of programming the ability to run simulations of their models.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The simulations are built from a series of mathematical algorithms, or models, and can vary with accuracy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Accuscore, which is licensed by companies such as ESPN, is a well-known simulation program for all major sports.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] It offers a detailed analysis of games through simulated betting lines, projected point totals and overall probabilities.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] With the increased interest in fantasy sports simulation models that predict individual player performance have gained popularity.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Companies like What If Sports and StatFox specialize in not only using their simulations for predicting game results but how well individual players will do as well.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Many people use models to determine whom to start in their fantasy leagues.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Another way simulations are helping the sports field is in the use of biomechanics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Models are derived and simulations are run from data received from sensors attached to athletes and video equipment.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Sports biomechanics aided by simulation models answer questions regarding training techniques such as the effect of fatigue on throwing performance (height of throw) and biomechanical factors of the upper limbs (reactive strength index; hand contact time).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Computer simulations allow their users to take models which before were too complex to run, and give them answers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulations have proven to be some of the best insights into both play performance and team predictability.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Simulation was used at Kennedy Space Center (KSC) to train and certify Space Shuttle engineers during simulated launch countdown operations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle engineering community would participate in a launch countdown integrated simulation before each Shuttle flight.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] This simulation is a virtual simulation where real people interact with simulated Space Shuttle vehicle and Ground Support Equipment (GSE) hardware.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, also known as S0044, involved countdown processes that would integrate many of the Space Shuttle vehicle and GSE systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Some of the Shuttle systems integrated in the simulation are the main propulsion system, RS-25, solid rocket boosters, ground liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, external tank, flight controls, navigation, and avionics.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation took place at the Kennedy Space Center Launch Control Center firing rooms.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The firing room used during the simulation is the same control room where real launch countdown operations are executed.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] As a result, equipment used for real launch countdown operations is engaged.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle vehicle hardware and related GSE hardware is simulated by mathematical models (written in Shuttle Ground Operations Simulator (SGOS) modeling language) that behave and react like real hardware.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] During the Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, engineers command and control hardware via real application software executing in the control consoles – just as if they were commanding real vehicle hardware.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] However, these real software applications do not interface with real Shuttle hardware during simulations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Instead, the applications interface with mathematical model representations of the vehicle and GSE hardware.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Consequently, the simulations bypass sensitive and even dangerous mechanisms while providing engineering measurements detailing how the hardware would have reacted.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Since these math models interact with the command and control application software, models and simulations are also used to debug and verify the functionality of application software.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The only true way to test GNSS receivers (commonly known as Sat-Nav's in the commercial world) is by using an RF Constellation Simulator.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] A receiver that may, for example, be used on an aircraft, can be tested under dynamic conditions without the need to take it on a real flight.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] The test conditions can be repeated exactly, and there is full control over all the test parameters. this is not possible in the 'real-world' using the actual signals.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] For testing receivers that will use the new Galileo (satellite navigation) there is no alternative, as the real signals do not yet exist.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Predicting weather conditions by extrapolating/interpolating previous data is one of the real use of simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Most of the weather forecasts use this information published by Weather bureaus.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] This kind of simulations helps in predicting and forewarning about extreme weather conditions like the path of an active hurricane/cyclone.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Numerical weather prediction for forecasting involves complicated numeric computer models to predict weather accurately by taking many parameters into account.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Strategy games—both traditional and modern—may be viewed as simulations of abstracted decision-making for the purpose of training military and political leaders (see History of Go for an example of such a tradition, or Kriegsspiel for a more recent example).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Many other video games are simulators of some kind.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] Such games can simulate various aspects of reality, from business, to government, to construction, to piloting vehicles (see above).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/simulation-p02] However, the connection between simulation and dissembling later faded out and is now only of linguistic interest.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] A **stochastic simulation** is a simulation of a system that has variables that can change stochastically (randomly) with individual probabilities.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Realizations of these random variables are generated and inserted into a model of the system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Outputs of the model are recorded, and then the process is repeated with a new set of random values.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] These steps are repeated until a sufficient amount of data is gathered.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] In the end, the distribution of the outputs shows the most probable estimates as well as a frame of expectations regarding what ranges of values the variables are more or less likely to fall in.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Often random variables inserted into the model are created on a computer with a random number generator (RNG).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The U(0,1) uniform distribution outputs of the random number generator are then transformed into random variables with probability distributions that are used in the system model.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] In order to determine the next event in a stochastic simulation, the rates of all possible changes to the state of the model are computed, and then ordered in an array.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Next, the cumulative sum of the array is taken, and the final cell contains the number R, where R is the total event rate.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This cumulative array is now a discrete cumulative distribution, and can be used to choose the next event by picking a random number z~U(0,R) and choosing the first event, such that z is less than the rate associated with that event.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] A probability distribution is used to describe the potential outcome of a random variable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Limits the outcomes where the variable can only take on discrete values.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] A random variable X is Bernoulli-distributed with parameter p if it has two possible outcomes usually encoded 1 (success or default) or 0 (failure or survival) where the probabilities of success and failure are $P(X=1)=p$ and $P(X=0)=1-p$ where $0\leq p\leq 1$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Define $X={\begin{cases}1&{\text{if heads comes up}}\\0&{\text{if tails comes up}}\end{cases}}$ For a fair coin, both realizations are equally likely.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Find the probability of getting exactly two heads.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This problem can be solved by looking at the sample space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] A poisson process is a process where events occur randomly in an interval of time or space.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] It can be shown that inter-arrival times for events is exponentially distributed with a cumulative distribution function (CDF) of $F(t)=1-e^{-t\lambda }$ .
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The inverse of the exponential CDF is given by $t=-{\frac {1}{\lambda }}\ln(u)$ where u is an $U(0,1)$ uniformly distributed random variable.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Simulating a Poisson process with a constant rate $\lambda$ for the number of events N that occur in interval $[t_{\text{start}},t_{\text{end}}]$ can be carried out with the following algorithm.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Published by Dan Gillespie in 1977, and is a linear search on the cumulative array.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Gillespie’s Stochastic Simulation Algorithm (SSA) is essentially an exact procedure for numerically simulating the time evolution of a well-stirred chemically reacting system by taking proper account of the randomness inherent in such a system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] It is rigorously based on the same microphysical premise that underlies the chemical master equation and gives a more realistic representation of a system’s evolution than the deterministic reaction rate equation (RRE) represented mathematically by ODEs.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] As with the chemical master equation, the SSA converges, in the limit of large numbers of reactants, to the same solution as the law of mass action.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Published 2000 by Gibson and Bruck the next reaction method improves over the first reaction method by reducing the amount of random numbers that need to be generated.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] To make the sampling of reactions more efficient, an indexed [priority queue] is used to store the reaction times.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] To make the computation of reaction propensities more efficient, a dependency graph is also used.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This dependency graph tells which reaction propensities to update after a particular reaction has fired.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] While more efficient, the next reaction method requires more complex data structures than either direct simulation or the first reaction method.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] These methods sort the cumulative array to reduce the average search depth of the algorithm.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The former runs a presimulation to estimate the firing frequency of reactions, whereas the latter sorts the cumulative array on-the-fly.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This is a binary search on the cumulative array, thus reducing the worst-case time complexity of reaction sampling to O (log M).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Use factored-out, partial reaction propensities to reduce the computational cost to scale with the number of species in the network, rather than the (larger) number of reactions.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The use of partial-propensity methods is limited to elementary chemical reactions, i.e., reactions with at most two different reactants.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Every non-elementary chemical reaction can be equivalently decomposed into a set of elementary ones, at the expense of a linear (in the order of the reaction) increase in network size.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] A general drawback of stochastic simulations is that for big systems, too many events happen which cannot all be taken into account in a simulation.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The following methods can dramatically improve simulation speed by some approximations.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Since the SSA method keeps track of each transition, it would be impractical to implement for certain applications due to high time complexity.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Gillespie proposed an approximation algorithm, the tau-leaping method which decreases computational time with minimal loss of accuracy.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Instead of taking incremental steps in time, keeping track of *X*(*t*) at each time step as in the SSA method, the tau-leaping method leaps from one subinterval to the next, approximating how many transitions take place during a given subinterval.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] It is assumed that the value of the leap, τ, is small enough that there is no significant change in the value of the transition rates along the subinterval [*t*, *t* + *τ*].
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This condition is known as the leap condition.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The tau-leaping method thus has the advantage of simulating many transitions in one leap while not losing significant accuracy, resulting in a speed up in computational time.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This method approximates reversible processes (which includes random walk/diffusion processes) by taking only net rates of the opposing events of a reversible process into account.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The main advantage of this method is that it can be implemented with a simple if-statement replacing the previous transition rates of the model with new, effective rates.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The model with the replaced transition rates can thus be solved, for instance, with the conventional SSA.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] While in discrete state space it is clearly distinguished between particular states (values) in continuous space it is not possible due to certain continuity.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The system usually change over time, variables of the model, then change continuously as well.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Continuous simulation thereby simulates the system over time, given differential equations determining the rates of change of state variables.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Many things actually are normally distributed, or very close to it.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] For example, height and intelligence are approximately normally distributed; measurement errors also often have a normal distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Exponential distribution describes the time between events in a Poisson process, i.e. a process in which events occur continuously and independently at a constant average rate.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The exponential distribution is popular, for example, in queuing theory when we want to model the time we have to wait until a certain event takes place.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Examples include the time until the next client enters the store, the time until a certain company defaults or the time until some machine has a defect.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Student's t-distribution are used in finance as probabilistic models of assets returns.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] For large values of *n*, the t-distribution doesn't significantly differ from a standard normal distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Usually, for values *n* > 30, the t-distribution is considered as equal to the standard normal distribution.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] It is often possible to model one and the same system by use of completely different world views.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Discrete event simulation of a problem as well as continuous event simulation of it (continuous simulation with the discrete events that disrupt the continuous flow) may lead eventually to the same answers.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Sometimes however, the techniques can answer different questions about a system.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] If we necessarily need to answer all the questions, or if we don't know what purposes is the model going to be used for, it is convenient to apply combined continuous/discrete methodology.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Similar techniques can change from a discrete, stochastic description to a deterministic, continuum description in a time-and space dependent manner.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The use of this technique enables the capturing of noise due to small copy numbers, while being much faster to simulate than the conventional Gillespie algorithm.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Furthermore, the use of the deterministic continuum description enables the simulations of arbitrarily large systems.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The main idea is that if it is necessary to know the average value of some random variable and its distribution cannot be stated, and if it is possible to take samples from the distribution, we can estimate it by taking the samples, independently, and averaging them.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] If there are sufficient samples, then the law of large numbers says the average must be close to the true value.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The central limit theorem says that the average has a Gaussian distribution around the true value.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] As a simple example, suppose we need to measure area of a shape with a complicated, irregular outline.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The Monte Carlo approach is to draw a square around the shape and measure the square.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Then we throw darts into the square, as uniformly as possible.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The fraction of darts falling on the shape gives the ratio of the area of the shape to the area of the square.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] In fact, it is possible to cast almost any integral problem, or any averaging problem, into this form.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] It is necessary to have a good way to tell if you're inside the outline, and a good way to figure out how many darts to throw.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Last but not least, we need to throw the darts uniformly, i.e., using a good random number generator.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] For simulation experiments (including Monte Carlo) it is necessary to generate random numbers (as values of variables).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The problem is that the computer is highly deterministic machine—basically, behind each process there is always an algorithm, a deterministic computation changing inputs to outputs; therefore it is not easy to generate uniformly spread random numbers over a defined interval or set.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] A random number generator is a device capable of producing a sequence of numbers which cannot be "easily" identified with deterministic properties.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] This sequence is then called a *sequence of stochastic numbers*.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] The algorithms typically rely on pseudorandom numbers, computer generated numbers mimicking true random numbers, to generate a realization, one possible outcome of a process.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Methods for obtaining random numbers have existed for a long time and are used in many different fields (such as gaming).
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] However, these numbers suffer from a certain bias.
[src:discrete-event-simulation/stochastic-simulation] Currently the best methods expected to produce truly random sequences are natural methods that take advantage of the random nature of quantum phenomena.
